In the Agricola he correctly characterises the results of the invasione of Julius Caesar ¹, and refers the long subsequent inaction to the civil wars, the ‘politic forgetiulness' oi Augustus, and the powerful influence oi his ideas on the mind of his successor¹; an explanation which he would probably have set forth with more detail in the body of his larger worlr.

It must be plain that Caesar's professed obJect in invading Britain⁸ could have been only very imperfectly and temporarily attained by the successes gained in it; and that, il he really believed the independence oi the island to be a standing menace to the peace ol Gaul, he must have contemplated some permanent occupation of it; and that this scheme, though thrown into the baclrground by the great expedition to the East, on which his energies were concentrated at the time oi his death, was among the ideas bequeathed by him to bis successors. He had shown that to land an army in the country and to penetrate its lorests was practic- able, and that the means of dividing its people by intrigue were ready to hand; that there would be tribes, such as were in his time the Trino- uantes oi Essex⁴, as ready to invite Roman interference as had been the Aedui and Remi of Gaul.

By the partition of the empire under the triumvirate, the execution ol the dictator’s ideas in respect of the occupatlon of Britain would sall to the share oi his nephew, who was apparently so lar penetrated with the necessity ol sustaining his reputation by an advance in that direction as to have at least made some show of preparing to invade this country as early as 720, a. c. 34, when he was recalled from Gaul by the Dalmatian rising ⁸.
